SIMPLE: single
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Single
<hw>Sin"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>singulus</ets>, a dim. from the root in <ets>simplex</ets> simple;
cf. OE. & OF. <ets>sengle</ets>, fr. L. <ets>singulus</ets>.
<ets>See</ets> <er>Simple</er>, and cf. <er>Singular</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One only, as distinguished from more than one;
consisting of one alone; individual; separate; <as>as, a <ex>single</ex>
star</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No <qex>single</qex> man is born with a right of controlling the
opinions of all the rest.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Alone; having no companion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who <qex>single</qex> hast maintained,⟦br⟧
Against revolted multitudes, the cause⟦br⟧
Of truth.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, unmarried; <as>as, a <ex>single</ex> man or
woman</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grows, lives, and dies in <qex>single</qex> blessedness.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Single</qex> chose to live, and shunned to wed.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not doubled, twisted together, or combined with
others; <as>as, a <ex>single</ex> thread; a <ex>single</ex> strand of a
rope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Performed by one person, or one on each side;
<as>as, a <ex>single</ex> combat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These shifts refuted, answer thy appellant, . . . ⟦br⟧
Who now defles thee thrice ti <qex>single</qex> fight.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Uncompounded; pure; unmixed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Simple ideas are opposed to complex, and <qex>single</qex> to
compound.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Not deceitful or artful; honest; sincere.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I speak it with a <qex>single</qex> heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Simple; not wise; weak; silly.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He utters such <qex>single</qex> matter in so infantly a
voice.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Single ale</b></col>, <col><b>Single
beer</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Single drink</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>small ale, etc., as contrasted with <contr>double ale</contr>, etc.,
which is stronger.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Nares.</au> --
<col><b>Single bill</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a written
engagement, generally under seal, for the payment of money, without a
penalty.</cd> <au>Burril.</au> -- <col><b>Single court</b></col>
<fld>(Lawn Tennis)</fld>, <cd>a court laid out for only two
players.</cd> -- <col><b>Single-cut file</b></col>. <cd>See the Note
under 4th <er>File</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Single entry</b></col>. <cd>See
under <er>Bookkeeping</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Single file</b></col>.
<cd>See under 1st <er>File</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Single flower</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a flower with but one set of petals, as a wild
rose.</cd> -- <col><b>Single knot</b></col>. -- <col><b>Single
whip</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a single rope running through a
fixed block.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Single</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Single
<hw>Sin"gle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Singled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Singling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
select, as an individual person or thing, from among a number; to choose
out from others; to separate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dogs who hereby can <qex>single</qex> out their master in the
dark.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His blood! she faintly screamed her mind⟦br⟧
Still <qex>singling</qex> one from all mankind.</q>
<rj><qau>More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sequester; to withdraw; to retire.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An agent <qex>singling</qex> itself from consorts.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take alone, or one by one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men . . . commendable when they are <qex>singled</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Single</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Single
<hw>Sin"gle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take the irregular gait
called single-foot; -- said of a horse. See
<er>Single-foot</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many very fleet horses, when overdriven, adopt a disagreeable
gait, which seems to be a cross between a pace and a trot, in which the
two legs of one side are raised almost but not quite, simultaneously.
Such horses are said to <qex>single</qex>, or to be single-footed.</q>
<rj><qau>W. S. Clark.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Single</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Single
<hw>Sin"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A unit; one; <as>as, to
score a <ex>single</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The reeled filaments of silk,
twisted without doubling to give them firmness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A handful of gleaned grain.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.
& Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law Tennis)</fld> <def>A game with but one player
on each side; -- usually in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <def>A hit by a batter which
enables him to reach first base only.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Single-acting</ent>⟦br⟧
